review: This is DEFINITELY not Harry Potter! I was very resistant to read this book for a long time because of my love for Harry and all things Hogwarts, but This is DEFINITELY not Harry Potter! I was very resistant to read this book for a long time because of my love for Harry and all things Hogwarts, but I'm so glad I did. I will admit, that it took me a good 50 pages or more to get over my initial shock at just how different a book this is. It's grown-up and gritty and ugly in it's realism. But, true to Rowling form, the characters are amazing! Not many of them are likeable, or even sympathetic, but they are wonderfully written. I could picture each character perfectly, and felt like I lived in their town I knew them so well. I found the book very compelling and extremely thought-provoking. I laughed, I raged, I cried...well done....more

review: Charming little story about a horse's journey through various hands during WWI. It's told from the horse's perspective, which was a new experience forCharming little story about a horse's journey through various hands during WWI. It's told from the horse's perspective, which was a new experience for me. My favorite thing about the book was that it didn't paint either side of the conflict as the "bad guy". The horse is owned by English and German soldiers alike and we see the good in both. I enjoyed the message that they were all just people caught up in a war that they didn't really want to be fighting.Other than that, it really did lack an emotional intensity to me. I was hoping for some crying or anxiety or something but never really felt moved, maybe I just need more of a human element to my stories.I haven't seen the movie, but I'm thinking this might be one of those rare occurrences when the movie is actually better than the book....more

review: This one was tough.In and of itself, I thought this book was excellent. Interesting characters, gorgeous writing, extremely well researched. I learnedThis one was tough.In and of itself, I thought this book was excellent. Interesting characters, gorgeous writing, extremely well researched. I learned so much about the Civil War era that I had never known. And reading about the abolitionists in Concord was fascinating. I enjoyed going through the journey of war with Mr. March and watching it change him forever. It was powerful and heartbreaking and fantastic!BUT...I love Louisa May Alcott's "Little Women"! I read it as a small girl for the first time and have loved it ever since. It's such a gorgeous romantic novel that, to me at least, was wonderful in it's idealism. The characters are strong and brave and selfless and good to the core so that even their suffering is beautiful. Realistic? No, probably not. Lovely and inspiring? Yes, absolutely. Enter Geraldine Brooks, who decides to take it upon herself to take a classic piece of literature and paint over it with "realism". She basically takes all of the romance and idealism of Alcott's novel and shatters it completely. I'm not sure I can ever forgive her for that. I wish she could've written this novel and just left the March family out of it!!...more

I don't even know where to start--the main character is completely unlikeable, she spends 80% of the book locked in internal debate about whether she's destined to be evil or not. NOTHING of import happens until the last 100 pages of the book. The "love story" is nonexistent: we're supposed to believe that these two people have this intense bond but the leading man is not even in 75% of the book, so it's definitely hard to buy. The only character I felt any kind of emotional connection with was Finbar, and that's only because I have residual feelings for him from the first book! And each book is getting longer and, yet, less fleshed out than the previous one. Lots of words, less and less action. Lame.I will say that the plot, in and of it itself, is sound. review: Definitely 3.5 stars.I didn't like this, as a whole, as much as the first one. BUT I did love the main characters. Liadan is strong and kind and just Definitely 3.5 stars.I didn't like this, as a whole, as much as the first one. BUT I did love the main characters. Liadan is strong and kind and just so good! Bran is brooding and tortured and deadly (my favorite combo) and also so good! Definitely more spice in their story than the love story in "Daughter of the Forest". There was more action, which is always fun. I absolutely adored the story-telling element throughout the book, it was wonderful to hear all of the Irish myths and folk tales interwoven in the novel. So why didn't I like it as much?----First off, it's overly wordy. Marillier could easily have written this book with -100 pages or so. The ending felt like it dragged on forever! She feels the need to spell out every minute detail, and it just gets tedious.Second, I didn't feel the emotional connection in the family that I did with the first book. In "Daughter of the Forest" my favorite thing was the intense bond between Sorcha and her six brothers. You felt that love on every page. In this book, she talks about their strong bonds, but I never really believed it. For a group of people that supposedly love each other, they seem to think very little of one another. There's no trust, which led to no honesty, which led to isolation for everyone. And I felt like it was taken to the extreme, once again it got tedious.That being said, I really did enjoy the plot. I am definitely interested in where the story is going and will keep on truckin!...more

review: This is billed as a fantasy, but truthfully it reads much more like an Irish folk tale, albeit a long, complex and pretty epic one! You love them, you hate them, you are scared with them, you hope with them and your heart breaks for them (a lot!). author: Wild, Peter*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Maybe closer to 2.5 stars...difficult to .Warning, I am going to make myself sound even more like a spazzy nerd than people already think I am, Maybe closer to 2.5 stars...difficult to .Warning, I am going to make myself sound even more like a spazzy nerd than people already think I am, but there's no other way to describe how I felt about this book. I love music. And I don't mean I enjoy listening and humming along to background noise. I mean, I LOVE MUSIC! I was raised on The Beatles and Simon & Garfunkel and my life has been one long musical journey that will never end. I absolutely love the way music can transport you to another world and evoke images and emotions that you didn't even know were there. I have been known, while listening to music, to imagine entire scenes and stories in my head. I can daydream for hours about these characters and places that were created from nothing more than a lyric or a mood of a particular song. Specifically, I adore The Smiths. They are one of my all-time favorite bands and I know all of their songs like I know the faces of my children. So, to me, the concept of this book was brilliant! If I was rating the book on just the concept, it would easily be 5 stars. Each short story inspired by a certain Smiths song. Gorgeous. Each author wrote a little foreward describing their inspiration and evolution from song to story. The stories themselves is what pushed the rating down. There were a few bizarre ones, a couple really sad ones, more than a few disturbing ones, a couple sweet ones...a good collection, but nothing that changed my life or made me want to re-read. What I did love was the shared experience with all of the authors. Even though I may not have daydreamed the same stories as them (not even once really), it was just fantastic to share that love of music and all the places it can take you. I'm so glad I walked into the library and saw this book on the shelf. ...more

review: I will quickly  this book, along with it's prequel "The Red Necklace" so I only have to write one .I will preface my harsh  by sayinI will quickly  this book, along with it's prequel "The Red Necklace" so I only have to write one .I will preface my harsh  by saying that, unfortunately for Sally Gardner, I had just finished re-reading "Deathly Hallows" right before I started these books...and I'm sure that had quite a lot to do with me being completely underwhelmed by these books. She's definetely no J.K. Rowling. Okay, onto it:I was so ready to really like these books, I loved the idea of a story set during the Reign of Terror in the French Revolution. I will say that the story itself was very compelling, I finished the books quickly and wanted to know how they were going to end. But that's about all the good I can say. I thought the writing was horrible...really juvenile and choppy. The characters (with maybe the exception of Yann) were very one-dimensional, the love story felt forced, the "magic" was never really explained in a way that made sense. The author uses a lot of "sudden realizations" rather than action/plot/dialogue to progress the story. I liked the first book more than the second, for sure. I thought Count Kalliovski was an uber-creepy bad guy in the first book...then she took it WAY TOO FAR in the second book, it was just a bad caricature of everything that people consider "evil". The ending was nonsensical and totally confusing.Really all I can say is that this story might have been really good in the hands of a really good writer. ...more

title: Brave New World
author: Huxley, Aldous
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I read this book in my 11th grade English class and haven't read it since. It was high school, so I didn't really recall much and wanted to read it agI read this book in my 11th grade English class and haven't read it since. It was high school, so I didn't really recall much and wanted to read it again. My first and most powerful thought was "Holy crow, I can't believe they let high schoolers read this! What with all the government sanctioned orgies and all."As a whole, I thoroughly enjoyed this novel. Huxley's writing is very vivid and almost over-the-top in its descriptiveness, but I really like that. It made the world he created seem 3-dimensional and real. The scientific "knowledge" behind the story was incredible, that alone warrants a 3-star rating. It's completely creative and unique and very well developed.Obviously, the book is totally creepy. Huxley has taken what is worst about science/government/morality/materialism... and magnified it to the umpteenth degree. It's not really meant to be taken 100% seriously, but in my opinion meant to cause us to examine our lives more closely. It's almost scary to see how many things about this fictional society are not too far off how we view things today, particularly in the moral issues the book brings to light. I have to say I thought it was a little offensive to paint capitalism as "the big bad", because capitalism in and of itself is not an evil thing. But different strokes for different folks, right? I really enjoyed the read, and found the ending to be very appropriate and extremely thought-provoking. I recommend....more

review: *SPOILER ALERT*Okay, so this book bordered on the ridiculous. There was prophecies and magic and voodoo and some more time travel. And you wouldn't be*SPOILER ALERT*Okay, so this book bordered on the ridiculous. There was prophecies and magic and voodoo and some more time travel. And you wouldn't believe the number of harrowing life-threatening situations that both of our main characters somehow slip away from unscathed. But all of that pails in comparison to the crazy coincidences that occur time and time again. It's pretty silly, especially when you consider that the setting of the novel spans throughout England, Scotland, France, Haiti & Jamaica.I mean really, the same Jewish philosopher that Jamie meets in France just happens to be wandering the jungles of Haiti where Claire is lost...The uptight priest who asks for Claire's assistance with his sick sister just happens also to be the crazy serial killer loose in Scotland and we also just bump into him again in Jamaica...the British soldier who's in love with Jamie (and honestly-how many British soldiers are gonna have the hots for Jamie throughout this series?) is conveniently enough the new Governor of Jamaica when Claire and Jamie arrive and need his assistance...when Jamie and Claire are cast out to sea in a storm their boat oddly enough finds it's way off course and to America which is where they were likely heading anyways. It's just one happy coincidence after another and it gets a little old. You'd think there was only like 30 people living throughout the region.This was definetely my least favorite of the 3 books so far, just because it seemed so unbelievable. Not sure if I'll read the fourth, especially since the ending of this one wasn't really a cliffhanger. If I find myself really bored and with nothing else on my nightstand I might take a stab......more

review: Hmmm.....first the bad:*WAY too many "romantic interludes" (and I use that term to be polite). There is a lot of romance in this book, much more than Hmmm.....first the bad:*WAY too many "romantic interludes" (and I use that term to be polite). There is a lot of romance in this book, much more than I am really comfortable with, and much more than is needed. To me, sex is not the same as love, and it shouldn't be used to try to illustrate (all the freaking time!) how two people feel about each other. I find it distracting to the actual emotional elements of a story.*the main character's quick transition from 1945 to 1743 didn't seem very believable. she didn't seem to have a really tough time believing that she was sent back in time, it just didn't fit in with her personality in my opinion.*the "bad guy", for lack of a better term, is despicable and evil and morally depraved in every way. I don't want to give details, but towards the end of the book there are some scenes that are so graphic and morally reprehensible that I found it hard to read. now the good:*I love Scottish men! There are very few things that I find more attractive than a Scottish accent and a kilt (I know I'm crazy). The author actually writes the dialogue like it's being said with a Scottish accent (does that make sense?). So I could really get into the characters and the entire world came alive for me.*the story was really compelling. I just couldn't wait to find out what would happen next. Obviously there are some fantastical elements, but I wasn't distracted by them. They seemed to fit in with the drama of the story and I just found myself being pulled along. All of the political intrigue and events of that time period are so fascinating to me, and when woven around these interesting characters I couldn't help but enjoy myself.*The characters that Babaldon creates are amazing. The leading lady is smart and funny and willfull. The leading man, Jamie--awesome. Not only because he's Scottish (but that certainly doesn't hurt), but because he's strong and good and just. The secondary characters are very multi-dimensional, you really feel like you can see and know them.All in all, I really enjoyed the book. It's kind of easy to skim over the areas that don't add anything to the story. I'm very excited to read the next book and see what happens!...more

I had a really tough time with about the first 1/3 of this book. Because of my total ignorance regarding anything angel related, I found myself very confused about the subject matter. I wasn't sure if I was supposed to mildly believe in the "myths" regarding angels (a la DaVinci Code) or if it was just completely fictional. So I didn't really have a basis for whether or not the story was working. That probably doesn't make any sense. Then about haflway through, I just gave myself up to the story and really started to enjoy it. I had a much easier time with the second half of the book. I was getting into the story and excited to see what was going to happen. But then, the ending came barreling out of nowhere, completely rushed and totally abrupt and I found myself reeling (and not in a good way). review: Sub-par is the word I'd use to describe this book. Not terrible, but not good either. The worst thing about this book, by far, is the horrible title! Sub-par is the word I'd use to describe this book. Not terrible, but not good either. The worst thing about this book, by far, is the horrible title! What was Philippa thinking? There are about a hundred different titles she could have used to write a book about Queen Elizabeth's love life. I felt like I had to hide the cover when I went out into public so people didn't think I was reading a trashy romance novel. I digress...the book. It basically blew every assumption I've ever had about Queen Elizabeth out of the water. She was not portrayed as the strong, powerful iconic Queen Elizabeth of legend. Instead, she was written as a simpering, weak-minded, undecisive, immature girl who let's her codependent "love" of a man make a complete fool of herself and nearly bring England to ruin. The male lead, Sir Robert Dudley, is reprehensible. I must've missed the part of the book where his blind overwhelming ambition somehow turned into love. Even his wife, who is supposed to be the sympathetic character, is completely annoying. I guess I did learn a little bit, but not enough to make this a book I'd recommend to anybody....more

review: Once again...3.5 stars. Hmmm....what can I say about this book? Read the blurb. I really liked it a lot. I thought the author did a good job of capturOnce again...3.5 stars. Hmmm....what can I say about this book? Read the blurb. I really liked it a lot. I thought the author did a good job of capturing a teenager's desire to find a "niche", "clique"-whatever you want to call it. I could really identify with Jessie being drawn to the "nerds" but still not being sure if she was willing to put herself out there to the judgement. I get it. I loved it when she just gave up and owned it. I loved her brother. I loved the fact that her family was a fully functional, loving family (honestly, how often do you see that in YA literature?). I loved that she fully admitted that she couldn't stand her nerdy crush's dorky tennis shoes (there's NOTHING wrong with that) and it didn't make her seem like a jerk. There was a hilarious camping/nerdy adventure at the end of the book that had me laughing out loud for about half an hour. Okay, disclaimers & mild annoyances:1. She mentions that she's an honor student/math nerd about a gazillion times. We get it! You're super smart and like school. 2. The conversations between the teenagers are (to me) a bit terrifying and what I would definetely classify as inappropriate. That being said, I live in a nice little bubble where I like to pretend that teenagers don't talk about "the birds and the bees" and say "S***" all the time. I'm guessing they were probably written fairly realistically, I just have trouble dealing.3. Maybe this is just me. But I HATED it that she continued to let her "friends" use and manipulate her even after she completely realized how crappy they were. Obviously, that situation is resolved by the end of the book, but her whimpiness lasted too long in my opinion.4. YA fiction...fairly predictable as usual.But I still enjoyed the book immensely and will be laughing about that camping trip for quite a while....more

review: This is the 12th book in this series and I can honestly say it's the first one I've enjoyed since about book 5. The writing was much easier to swallowThis is the 12th book in this series and I can honestly say it's the first one I've enjoyed since about book 5. The writing was much easier to swallow, and the plot was progressing nicely (something that hasn't happened in the last 4 or so books). Not to speak ill of the dead, but I just enjoy Brandon Sanderson's writing so much more than Robert Jordan's. My biggest beef with this series is the many countless subplots going on...I feel it's a bit like "Lost" on ABC...too many stories to keep track of. I feel like things are starting to get wrapped up now so it was a very refreshing change of pace. The only reason I didn't give the book 5 stars is because I still just can't deal with all of the characters self-involved whining and complaining and their ridiculous senses of pride. Even the main character, who is basically the savior of this world, is completely self-involved in his selflessness. Does that make sense? But the ending of the book gave me a bit of hope on that front. I have to say...for the first time in a long time, I'm actually really looking forward to the next book in the series....more

review: The premise of this book was very intriguing to me. A group of people, all from different countries, are at a presidential dinner party in an unnamed The premise of this book was very intriguing to me. A group of people, all from different countries, are at a presidential dinner party in an unnamed country, when revolutionaries storm the house and take everyone hostage. What ensues is a nearly 6-month long captivity for 39 men and 1 woman plus 15 "terrorists". I thought this would be a fantastic tale, full of rich characters...since they're all stuck in a house for 6 months there's bound to be some great stories (or backstories or something), right? I must say I was pretty unhappy with the character development. I felt like I didn't really get to know anybody very well, the love stories were very contrived and forced, the ending was incredibly anti-climatic and then really bizarre. I wasn't even sure about the motives of the revolutionaries, the author spoke in vague generalities about "freedom for the people" and I found myself asking, 'freedom from what'? And the ending...after nearly 6 months of captivity, the resolution (I use that term very loosely here) is written in less than two pages!! I kept reading because I was hoping for more details and a deeper feeling, but unfortunately neither one came to me. ...more

review: Honestly, one of the best books I've read in quite awhile. I didn't expect to enjoy it that much because the entire story is told through various lettHonestly, one of the best books I've read in quite awhile. I didn't expect to enjoy it that much because the entire story is told through various letters, but I absolutely loved every page. I couldn't put it down. The characters are painted so vividly, you feel like you know them personally. The main character is witty and self-deprecating and strong and just lovely in every way. You learn a bit of history about WWII, but the main theme of the book is the strength of the human spirit and of course (my favorite) love. Both heartwarming and heartbreaking, it's a fantastic book, I can't think why anybody wouldn't love it!!...more
